 the “invention” of the nation. Capitals capture the imagination of natives, visitors and outsiders alike, yet also express the outcomes of power struggles within the political systems in which they operate. This volume addresses the reciprocal relationships between identity, regime formation, urban planning, and public architecture in the Western world. It examines the role of urban design and architecture in expressing (or hiding) ideological beliefs and political agenda.  Case studies include “old” capitals such as Rome, Vienna, Berlin and Warsaw; “new” ones such as Washington DC, Ottawa, Canberra, Ankara, Bonn, and Brasília; and the “European” capital Brussels. Each case reflects the authors’ different disciplinary backgrounds in architecture, history, political science, and urban studies, demonstrating the value of an interdisciplinary approach to studying cities.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 0aArchitecture and state. 0aCapitals (Cities)vCase studies. 0aCity planningxHistory. 0aDemocracy and architecture. 0aDemocracy. 0aNational characteristics. 0aPower (Social sciences) 0aPower (Social sciences). 0aPublic architecture. 0aPublic spacesxPolitical aspects. 0aSymbolism in architecture. 7aARCHITECTURE / Urban & Land Use Planning.2bisacsh1 aAsendorf, Christoph, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBeyme, Klaus von, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBlau, Eve, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCrowley, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHein, Carola, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKirk, Terry, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMinkenberg, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov